{"title_page": "Omar Sneed", "text_new": "{{Under construction}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name            = Omar Sneed\n| image           = Omar Sneed (2009).JPG\n| width           = 220\n| caption         = Sneed in 2009\n| team            = \n| league          =\n| position        = [[Small forward]] / [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 6\n| weight_lb       = 239\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1976|10|09}}\n| birth_place     = [[Beaumont, Texas]]\n| nationality     = American\n| high_school     = [[West Brook High School|West Brook]]<br>(Beaumont, Texas)\n| college         = [[San Jacinto College|San Jacinto]] (1995\u20131997)<br>[[Memphis Tigers men's basketball|Memphis]] (1997\u20131999)\n| draft_year      = 1999\n| draft_round     = \n| draft_pick      = \n| draft_team      = \n| career_start    = 1999\n| career_end      = 2015\n| years1          = 1999\n| team1           = [[Sabios de Manizales]]\n| years2          = 2000\n| team2           = [[Melco Ieper]]\n| years3          = 2000\n| team3           = San L\u00e1zaro\n| years4          = 2000\u20132001\n| team4           = [[BSW Weert]]\n| years5          = 2001\u20132002\n| team5          = [[BT Holstra Wevelgem|Power Wevelgem]]\n| years6          = 2002\u20132003\n| team6          = [[Znicz Pruszk\u00f3w]]\n| years7          = 2003\u20132004\n| team7           = [[London Towers]]\n| years8          = 2004\u20132005\n| team8           = [[Ironi Ashkelon|Elitzur Ashkelon]]\n| years9          = 2005\u20132006\n| team9           = [[Maccabi Rishon LeZion (basketball)|Maccabi Rishon LeZion]]\n| years10          = 2006\u20132008\n| team10           = [[PBC Lokomotiv Kuban|Lokomotiv Rostov]]\n| years11          = 2008\n| team11           = [[Kaveh Tehran BC|Kaveh]]\n| years12          = 2008\n| team12           = [[Saba Battery Tehran BC|Saba Battery]]\n| years13          = 2008\n| team13           = [[Maccabi Rishon LeZion (basketball)|Maccabi Rishon LeZion]]\n| years14          = 2008\u20132009\n| team14           = [[Hapoel Jerusalem B.C.|Hapoel Jerusalem]]\n| years15          = 2009\u20132010\n| team15           = [[Ironi Ashkelon|Elitzur Ashkelon]]\n| years16          = 2010\u20132011\n| team16           = [[Kar\u015f\u0131yaka Basket|Pinar Kar\u015f\u0131yaka]]\n| years17          = 2011\n| team17           = [[Defensor Sporting]]\n| years18          = 2012\n| team18           = [[Mersin B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyesi S.K.|Mersin BB]]\n| years19          = 2012\n| team19           = [[Powerade Tigers]]\n| years20          = 2012\u20132013\n| team20           = [[Mersin B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyesi S.K.|Mersin BB]]\n| years21          = 2014\u20132015\n| team21           = [[Ankara DS\u0130 S.K.|Ankara DS\u0130]]\n| highlights   =\n*2\u00d7 [[Israeli Basketball Premier League Quintet]] ([[2005\u201306 Israeli Basketball Super League|2006]], [[2008\u201309 Israeli Basketball Super League|2009]])\n*[[Dutch Basketball League|DBL]] All-Star ([[2000\u201301 Eredivisie (basketball)|2001]])\n*[[List of Dutch Basketball League season scoring leaders|DBL Top scorer]] (2001)\n*Second-team All-[[Conference USA|C-USA]] (1999)\n*First-team All-C-USA (1998)\n| bbr             =\n}}\n'''Omar Shariff Sneed'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/34930/sid/5084/tid/4661/_/2007_EuroCup/index.html|title=Omar Shariff Sneed's profile 2007 EuroCup|website=[[FIBA]].com|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> (born October 9, 1976) is an American former professional basketball player. A [[Texas]] native, Sneed played [[high school basketball]] at [[West Brook High School|West Brook]] in [[Beaumont, Texas|Beaumont]]. He then played two years in [[junior college]] at [[San Jacinto College|San Jacinto]], being named a first team [[National Junior College Athletic Association|NJCAA]] All-American.<ref name=guide28>{{Cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/sidearm.sites/gotigersgo.com/documents/2015/5/27/_m_baskbl__1998-99CompleteB-ballmedia.pdf|title=1998-99 University of Memphis Basketball Media Guide|publisher=[[University of Memphis]]|date=1998|page=28|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He played his junior and senior seasons in the [[NCAA Division I]] with the [[Memphis Tigers men's basketball|Memphis Tigers]], being a two-time all-conference selection. After going undrafted in the [[1999 NBA draft]], Sneed started his professional career in [[Colombia]]. Over the years he has played in several countries in [[Asia]], [[Europe]] and [[South America]], being the top scorer of the Dutch league in 2001 and being named in the top-5 of the [[Israeli Basketball Premier League]]. He retired from professional basketball in 2015 after a season in the Turkish second division.\n\n== High school career ==\nSneed was born in Texas to Robert and Gertrude Sneed.<ref name=guide28 /> He attended [[West Brook High School]] in [[Beaumont, Texas|Beaumont]], where he averaged 32 points per game as a sophomore in the 1992\u201393 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://texashsbasketballrecords.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Download-File-boys-scoring-greats-ilovepdf-compressed.pdf|title=ALL-TIME SCORING RECORDS 16-17|website=texashsbasketballrecords.com|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=SCOREBOARD|newspaper=[[The Galveston Daily News]]|date=February 27, 1993|page=14}}</ref> As a senior, Sneed averaged 21 points and 13 rebounds per game,<ref name=guide28 /> being selected in the All-State First Team by the Texas Association of Basketball Coaches (TABC).<ref>{{Cite news|title=BOYS ALL-STATE BASKETBALL TEAMS|date=March 23, 1995|newspaper=[[Seguin Gazette]]|page=4}}</ref>\n\n== College career ==\n=== San Jacinto ===\nSneed was recruited by [[NCAA Division I]] programs [[Houston Cougars men's basketball|Houston]] and [[Texas Longhorns men's basketball|Texas]]<ref name=odessa>{{Cite news|title=BASKETBALL|newspaper=[[The Odessa American]]|date=March 8, 1997|page=31}}</ref> during his high school career. He signed with Houston in April 1995;<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.thedailycougar.com/vol60/95-04-13.html|title=UH BASKETBALL HONORS PLAYER ACHIEVEMENTS|newspaper=[[The Daily Cougar]]|author=Ram\u00edrez, Jason Paul|date=April 13, 1995|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=College Selected Signings|newspaper=[[The Daily Oklahoman]]|date=May 25, 1995|page=26}}</ref> however, Sneed did not qualify academically to play in the [[NCAA]], and he decided to play for a [[junior college]] in the [[NJCAA]],<ref name=odessa /> choosing [[San Jacinto College]], a community college in the [[Houston, Texas|Houston]] area which competed in the [[List of NJCAA Division I schools|NJCAA Division I]].\n\nIn his freshman season Sneed averaged 21 points and 10.9 rebounds per game, shooting 60.3% from the field.<ref name=guide28 /> At the end of the season, Sneed was named in the All-TEC first team as one of the best players in the conference.<ref>{{Cite news|title=TEC men's all-conference|newspaper=[[Longview News-Journal]]|date=March 6, 1996|page=12}}</ref> As a sophomore, Sneed played along future [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] player [[Steve Francis]], who had joined San Jacinto as a freshman in 1996; in a game against [[Blinn College]], Sneed scored a career-high 43 points.<ref name=guide28 /> Sneed averaged 24.2 points and 11.3 rebounds per game, shooting 58.2% from the field, and was ranked 7th in the nation among junior college players.<ref name=guide28 /> San Jacinto reached the championship game during the 1997 [[NJCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NJCAA Division I Tournament]] in [[Hutchinson, Kansas]], losing to [[Indian Hills Community College]] of [[Iowa]], 80\u201389.<ref name=guide28 /> Sneed was the top scorer of the game with 26 points (18 in the first half).<ref>{{Cite news|title=Indian Hills (Iowa) 89, San Jacinto (Texas) 80|newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]]|date=March 23, 1997|page=39}}</ref> At the end of the season, Sneed was named the 1997 TEAC MVP, and was included in the All-Conference First Team;<ref>{{Cite news|title=Dragons named to TEAC team|newspaper=[[The Paris News]]|date=April 6, 1997|page=15}}</ref> he was also a first-team All-American, and the ''[[Basketball Times]]'' named him JUCO National Player of the Year.<ref name=guide28 />\n\n=== Memphis ===\nIn May 1997, Sneed signed a [[National Letter of Intent]] to play for [[Memphis Tigers men's basketball|Memphis]] in the NCAA Division I.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Men's letters of intent|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=May 8, 1997|page=71}}</ref> He chose to wear jersey number 31 and made his debut with the Tigers in the season opener against [[Louisiana\u2013Monroe Warhawks|Louisiana\u2013Monroe]] on November 15, 1997; in the following game, he recorded a double-double with 23 points and 10 rebounds against [[Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball|Vanderbilt]].<ref name=guide44>''1998-99 University of Memphis Basketball Media Guide''. University of Memphis. 1998. p. 44.</ref> On December 20, he scored a new career-high 30 points against [[Tennessee Volunteers basketball|Tennessee]].<ref name=guide44 /> On February 2, 1998 Sneed was named [[Conference USA]] Player of the Week;<ref name=guide28 /> on February 11, he posted 37 points and 20 rebounds, career-highs at Memphis, in a double overtime loss against [[DePaul Blue Demons men's basketball|DePaul]].<ref name=guide44 /> On February 21, he scored 34 points (with 8 rebounds) against [[Louisville Cardinals men's basketball|Louisville]], earning his second Conference USA Player of the Week nomination on February 23.<ref name=guide28 /> He had 12 [[double double]]s in the season,<ref name=guide82>''1998-99 University of Memphis Basketball Media Guide''. University of Memphis. 1998. p. 82.</ref> leading the team in scoring in 18 games and in rebounding in 16 games.<ref name=guide61>''1998-99 University of Memphis Basketball Media Guide''. University of Memphis. 1998. p. 61.</ref> He also led the Conference USA in scoring (22.7 points per game) and rebounding (9.7) in conference games only (16 appearances).<ref name=guide82 /> He started all 29 games, playing a total of 1,053 minutes (36.3 per game),<ref name=guide28 /> and averaged 20.9 points and 9.2 rebounds for the season, shooting 58.5% from the field. At the end of the season he was named the team MVP, and a first-team All-Conference USA selection.<ref name=guide28 /> He was also named in the [[USBWA]] All-District 4 team and in the [[NABC]] District 7 First Team, and the Tennessee Sports Writers Association named him Player of the Year.<ref name=guide28 />\n\n===College statistics===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[1997\u201398 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1997\u201398]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[1997\u201398 Memphis Tigers men's basketball team|Memphis]]\n| '''29''' || '''29''' || '''36.3''' || '''.585''' || '''.238''' || '''.667''' || '''9.2''' || '''2.2''' || '''1.6''' || '''0.4''' || '''20.9'''\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[1998\u201399 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1998\u201399]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[1998\u201399 Memphis Tigers men's basketball team|Memphis]]\n| 28 || 28 || 31.8 || .506 || .162 || .642 || 7.5 || 1.7 || 1.4 || 0.2 || 16.7\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | '''Career'''\n| align=\"left\" |\n| 57 || 57 || 34.1 || .548 || .190 || .655 || 8.4 || 2.0 || 1.5 || 0.3 || 18.8\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.proballers.com/basketball/player/20978/omar-sneed Career stats at ProBallers.com]\n*[https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Omar-Sneed/Summary/9669 Profile at RealGM.com]\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/omar-sneed-1.html College stats at Sports-Reference.com]\n*[http://db.basketball.nl/db/overzicht/spelersdossier.pl?detail=Dossier&spl_ID=1591 Dutch league stats]\n*[https://basket.co.il/player.asp?PlayerId=1141&lang=en Israeli league stats]\n*[http://www.tblstat.net/pd.asp?p=1679 Turkish league stats]\n\n{{DBL Top Scorer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sneed, Omar}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Belgium]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Colombia]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Iran]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Israel]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Poland]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Russia]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Turkey]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Texas]]\n[[Category:BSW (basketball club) players]]\n[[Category:Hapoel Jerusalem B.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ironi Ashkelon players]]\n[[Category:Kar\u015f\u0131yaka basketball players]]\n[[Category:London Towers players]]\n[[Category:Maccabi Rishon LeZion basketball players]]\n[[Category:Memphis Tigers men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Mersin B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyesi S.K. players]]\n[[Category:PBC Lokomotiv-Kuban players]]\n[[Category:Philippine Basketball Association imports]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Powerade Tigers players]]\n[[Category:San Jacinto Central Ravens men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Small forwards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Beaumont, Texas]]\n\n[[he:\u05e2\u05d5\u05de\u05d0\u05e8 \u05e1\u05e0\u05d9\u05d3]]\n", "text_old": "{{Under construction}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name            = Omar Sneed\n| image           = Omar Sneed (2009).JPG\n| widt